\begin_layout Subparagraph
4.
 Find the area of the shaded region below *(picture not included).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are given the two outer bounds, -2 and 3.
 Now we must find the interior intersections.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\frac{x^{3}}{3}-x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=\frac{x}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)\implies\frac{x^{3}}{3}-x=\frac{x}{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x^{3}}{3}-\frac{4x}{3}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3}x(x^{2}-4)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore the roots are 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\pm2.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus to calculate the total area bounded within this interval by these two
 functions, we need to specify, which function is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

larger
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 function over given intervals.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the total area bounded by these two functions equals:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-2}^{0}f(x)-g(x)+\int_{0}^{2}g(x)-f(x)+\int_{2}^{3}f(x)-g(x)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=\int_{-2}^{0}\frac{x^{3}}{3}-x-\frac{x}{3}+\int_{0}^{2}\frac{x}{3}-\frac{x^{3}}{3}+x+\int_{2}^{3}\frac{x^{3}}{3}-x-\frac{x}{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can easily solve for this value by splitting all three definite integrals
 into their component pieces and integrating separately (by applying basic
 power rule).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, the total area bounded by the shaded region equals:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=\frac{4}{3}+\frac{4}{3}+\frac{25}{12}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=\frac{19}{4}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

